      <title>Fed keeps interest rates steady. And, Catholics around the world wait for a new Pope</title>
      <author>Brittney Melton</author>
      <link>https://www.npr.org/2025/05/08/g-s1-64950/up-first-newsletter-federal-reserve-interest-rates-deportations-libya-india-pakistan</link>
      <comments>https://text.npr.org/2025/05/08/g-s1-64950/up-first-newsletter-federal-reserve-interest-rates-deportations-libya-india-pakistan</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.npr.org/2025/05/08/g-s1-64950/up-first-newsletter-federal-reserve-interest-rates-deportations-libya-india-pakistan</guid>
      <pubDate>Thu, 08 May 2025 10:40:58 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div id="storytext" class="storytext storylocation linkLocation"&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Good morning. You're reading the Up First newsletter. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/newsletter/news" target="_blank"&gt;Subscribe&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; here to get it delivered to your inbox, and &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/podcasts/510318/up-first/" target="_blank"&gt;listen&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; to the Up First podcast for all the news you need to start your day.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Today's top stories&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Federal Reserve held interest rates steady yesterday&lt;/strong&gt; as it waits to see how President Trump's trade war affects the U.S. economy. The financial markets anticipated the Fed's decision to maintain the &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/05/07/nx-s1-5387499/federal-reserve-interest-rates-trump-tariffs-inflation" target="_blank"&gt;benchmark borrowing rate&lt;/a&gt; at between 4.25% and 4.5%, despite the president's calls for a reduction.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-64810" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 8256;         --source-height: 4644;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8256x4644+0+346/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F26%2Fea%2Fcb96ef1743cbb650cddf45b6d912%2Fgettyimages-2164059266.jpg" class="img" alt="US Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell speaks during a news conference after a Federal Open Market Committee meeting at the Federal Reserve in Washington, DC, on July 31, 2024. The US Federal Reserve left its key lending rate unchanged again on July 31 and said it had made &amp;quot;some further progress&amp;quot; in its inflation fight. Policymakers voted unanimously to maintain the US central bank&amp;#039;s benchmark interest rate between 5.25 percent and 5.50 percent, the Fed announced in a statement, adding it was &amp;quot;attentive to the risks to both sides of its dual mandate.&amp;quot; (Photo by ROBERTO SCHMIDT / AFP) (Photo by ROBERTO SCHMIDT/AFP via Getty Images)" loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell and his colleagues kept interest rates unchanged Wednesday. President Trump has criticized the central bank for not lowering rates.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Roberto Schmidt/AFP/Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;NPR's Scott Horsley tells &lt;em&gt;Up First &lt;/em&gt;that Federal Reserve policymakers are watching out for&lt;/strong&gt; signs of increased pressure on prices that could rekindle inflation or a weakening in the job market. Horsley says one reason Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1249919781:1269278464" target="_blank"&gt;isn't feeling a sense of urgency&lt;/a&gt; to cut interest rates is because the Fed chairman says the economy is still in solid shape.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Trump administration plans to deport migrants without legal status to Libya&lt;/strong&gt;, a country troubled by armed conflict, as early as next week. The U.S. military would conduct these deportations. In recent months, U.S. officials have been &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/05/07/nx-s1-5389739/libya-immigration-crackdown-trump-deportations" target="_blank"&gt;negotiating with various countries&lt;/a&gt; willing to accept individuals deported from the U.S. Earlier this week, Rwanda's foreign minister mentioned that his country is in discussions with Washington about accepting deportees. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;One of the main goals of this plan is to send migrants farther away, so they can't cross back over U.S. borders&lt;/strong&gt;, according to NPR's Ximena Bustillo. A judge in Massachusetts issued an injunction blocking Homeland Security from removing migrants and sending them to countries they're not originally from. The administration found workarounds to the injunction by using other agencies to remove people from the U.S. Last night, the same judge issued another order clarifying that Homeland Security &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1249919781:1269278464" target="_blank"&gt;cannot exploit a loophole&lt;/a&gt;. The order also says that no agency may deport individuals to a country they are not from without allowing them proper time to contest the removal.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pakistan's military spokesman, Lieutenant General Ahmad Sharif, said they shot down Indian drones flying over major cities this morning. &lt;/strong&gt;This action follows India's recent strikes on multiple targets across Pakistan on Tuesday, marking the most extensive military action India has taken in over 50 years. India says its actions were in response to terror attacks launched from Pakistani territory last month. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;Sharif accused India of sending 25 Israeli-made drones this morning. &lt;/strong&gt;He says the Pakistani military shot down all of the drones except one that targeted an old airport in Lahore, Pakistan's second-largest city. One civilian was killed in that attack, Sharif said. The Pakistani deputy prime minister confirmed this morning that national advisers of both countries had been in talks and &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1249919781:1269278464" target="_blank"&gt;things were looking hopeful&lt;/a&gt;, NPR's Diaa Hadid says. But that was before Pakistan accused India of sending drones.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Black smoke was seen rising from the Sistine Chapel on the second day of the papal conclave&lt;/strong&gt;, indicating that the 133 Catholic cardinals had not chosen a successor to the late Pope Francis. Starting today, cardinals will participate in &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/05/08/nx-s1-5390452/pope-conclave-second-day" target="_blank"&gt;up to four rounds of voting&lt;/a&gt; each day until a new pope is elected. Stay up-to-date on the election of the next pope &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/series/g-s1-64080/conclave-2025" target="_blank"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Life advice&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-64817" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4000;         --source-height: 2250;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+701/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4a%2Faf%2Fc7bc43834e7895957962c9492e4b%2Ffields-npr-life-kit-j3v2.jpg" class="img" alt="An illustration showing a person wearing a baseball cap and carrying an unzipped backpack on one shoulder, as they look over their shoulder. Items essential fo a &amp;quot;go bag&amp;quot; for emergencies float into the bag from the top right corner of the frame, including, a lighter, a rope, duct tape, a charger, medication, menstrual products, a pocket knife, a flashlight, non-perishable foods, documents, and water. " loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Only about half of Americans have assembled a stash of emergency supplies. To make the process less overwhelming, "start with what you already have," says Alyssa Provencio, a professor at the University of Central Oklahoma who researches emergency and disaster management.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Olivia Fields for NPR                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Creating an emergency go bag can feel daunting and costly, but it doesn't have to be. Many people struggle to know what items to include, which might explain why only half of Americans report having assembled or updated their emergency supplies. To make the process easier and more budget-friendly, consider building your kit gradually over time. Experts in emergency preparedness shared helpful tips with &lt;em&gt;Life Kit &lt;/em&gt;on &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/05/07/nx-s1-5320173/budget-emergency-go-bag" target="_blank"&gt;how to create an affordable kit&lt;/a&gt; and what items to prioritize. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎒 A sturdy bag is key to holding your food and supplies. Bonus points if it has wheels. Don't feel you need to buy a new bag; an old duffel bag will work.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎒 Pack three days of lightweight, calorie-dense food, like peanut butter or tuna in pouches.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎒 Premade first-aid kits are convenient, but it will be cheaper to make your own. Include items like bandages, gauze, alcohol and pain relievers.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎒 Include photocopies of insurance work, birth certificate and the deed to your home. Put these important documents in zip-close bags for protection from water damage.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎒 A power bank will charge your phone, allowing you to make emergency calls.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;p&gt;For more guidance on how to create an emergency go bag, &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=nx-s1-5320173:g-s1-64574" target="_blank"&gt;listen to this episode of NPR's&lt;i&gt; Life Kit&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. Subscribe to &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/newsletter/life-kit" target="_blank"&gt;the &lt;i&gt;Life Kit &lt;/i&gt;newsletter&lt;/a&gt; for expert advice on love, money, relationships and more.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Picture show&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-63834" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 2880;         --source-height: 1621;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2880x1621+257+367/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5b%2Fd8%2F69c0c6f24a678df76e9160cb05fa%2Flemons-race024.JPG" class="img" alt="A 1990 Mercedes-Benz 190E participates in the 24 Hours of Lemons rally in Kershaw, S.C., on April 26. The race features cars that cost $500 or less." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 A 1990 Mercedes-Benz 190E participates in the 24 Hours of Lemons rally in Kershaw, S.C., on April 26. The race features cars that cost $500 or less.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Sam Wolfe for NPR                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The 24 Hours of Lemons event is an endurance race with a twist: The participating cars cost less than $500. This racing series promotes itself as an event for everyday people. The vehicles are not only economical but also quite eccentric. At a recent race, there was a Toyota Yaris painted to resemble Gary, the pet snail from &lt;em&gt;Spongebob Squarepants&lt;/em&gt;, and a Honda Civic topped with items like a lawnmower, squirrels, and flamingos. Teams are also encouraged to wear costumes, adding to the fun atmosphere. The event began over 15 years ago in California and now features 23 races a year across the country. Check out photos of the &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/05/02/nx-s1-5382362/lemons-tour-24-hours-cars-endurance-race" target="_blank"&gt;uniquely designed race cars&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you go&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-63583" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4524;         --source-height: 2545;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4524x2545+17+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F75%2Fd7%2F8c64ea1345c78e43da4da7343aca%2Fwellington-jpg.jpg" class="img" alt="The Wellington, Pine Hill, N.Y." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ol class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;The National Trust for Historic Preservation announced yesterday America's &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/05/07/nx-s1-5371295/endangered-historic-places-preservation" target="_blank"&gt;11 most endangered historic places&lt;/a&gt; in 2025. This year, the list includes not only buildings, but entire communities.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;The seventh Disney theme park will be built in Abu Dhabi, according to the Walt Disney Company. It will &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/05/07/nx-s1-5389601/disney-park-abu-dhabi" target="_blank"&gt;feature a spiraling castle&lt;/a&gt; that appears to be made of crystal.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;According to a new study, humans have &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/05/07/nx-s1-5387502/deep-seafloor-ocean-mapped-rhode-island" target="_blank"&gt;seen less than 0.001%&lt;/a&gt; of the deep seafloor, which is home to bizarre creatures like the vampire squid.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This newsletter was edited by &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/people/859721331/suzanne-nuyen"target="_blank"   &gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Suzanne Nuyen&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
